More than 9000 people were arrested in KwaZulu-Natal during multi-disciplinary operations last month, with nearly 200 arrested for murder. Last month, police in the province embarked on numerous operations which they said aimed at reducing the high levels of crime, particularly contact crimes. KZN police spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Nqobile Gwala said various operations were undertaken in targeted areas that had specific crime threats and the operations were conducted in all eleven districts in the province. Gwala said a total of 9169 people were arrested for various crimes. According to Gwala, police managed to arrest 198 people for murder, 157 for attempted murder, 291 for robberies, 259 for rape, 2033 for assault, 289 for burglary and 1568 people were arrested for drug related crimes. She said large quantities of drugs such heroin, cocaine, ecstasy, crystal meth, and dagga were seized by police. “Counterfeit goods, including cigarettes were also seized during police operations. Stolen property including 205 vehicles that were stolen or robbed from their lawful owners, were recovered by police. Another 43 vehicles were seized after they were used in the commission of crimes,” said Gwala. She said police also seized 282 firearms during these operations. Among the firearms seized were 16 homemade firearms, 237 revolvers, 15 rifles, 9 shotguns, and five semi-automatic firearms, she said. She said a total of 2897 rounds of ammunition were also seized during operations, and livestock such as cattle, donkeys, goats and sheep were recovered by police.